        <h3>💡 Bottom Line</h3>
        <p>The afternoon's headline is Kharg Island — Trump struck every military target on Iran's oil lifeline while deliberately sparing the oil infrastructure. <strong>This is coercive diplomacy, not conflict resolution.</strong> The message to Tehran: reopen Hormuz or we come back for the oil terminals. But Iran's options are narrow and its leadership may be incapacitated — Hegseth claims Mojtaba Khamenei was "disfigured," and Iranians are questioning who's really in charge after his first address came via a TV presenter. <strong>A leaderless Iran under fire is the most dangerous scenario for markets.</strong> Meanwhile, the crisis is metastasizing: North Korea fired a ballistic missile while US troops redeploy from Japan to the Middle East, widening the Indo-Pacific security gap. Trump admitted Putin is "helping" Iran — acknowledging a dimension he denied just last week. Lebanon's death toll hit 773. US mortgage rates surged to a 7-month high, killing the spring housing season. <strong>For Japan specifically:</strong> the BOJ meeting Tuesday-Wednesday is now the week's most critical event. With Nikkei at 53,820 (−9.3% from ATH), Honda posting its first loss in 70 years, US troops leaving Japan-based units, North Korea launching missiles, and ¥160 days away — the convergence of pressures on Japan is extraordinary. The only thing preventing a score below 13 is that Trump spared Kharg's oil infrastructure, signaling he wants compliance rather than destruction. If that restraint holds, there's a path back. If it doesn't, we're heading to single digits.</p>
